Ed,

&gt; Thanks for the response. The only thing that changes between my tests is 
&gt; the DB URL (string). Having to maintain a subclass for each db AND a 
&gt; test suite listing all of the subclasses seems onerous. It seems like I 
&gt; should be able to simply give a list of DB URLs and have JUnit execute a 
&gt; setup method ONCE for each set of tests. What&#39;s the easiest way to do this?

Put the test suite in each subclass, not in the base class. If all your 
subclasses need to do is return a URL, then it&#39;s not very onerous at 
all. The Oracle-specific subclass, for example, will look like:

public class OracleDbTest
extends DbTestBase {

   @BeforeClass
   public static void initDb() {
     initDbWithUrl(&quot;file:///some/oracle/url&quot;);
   }

   @AfterClass
   public static void cleanup() {
     cleanupDb();
   }

   public static junit.framework.Test suite() {
     return new JUnit4TestAdapter(OracleDbTest.class);
   }
}

and the base class will be

public abstract class DbTestBase {

   @Test
   public final void someTest() { ... }

   protected static final void initDbWithUrl(String url) {
     ...
   }

   protected static final void cleanupDb() {
     ...
   }

}

If maintaining a *DbTest class for each DB implementation is too much 
maintenance for your taste, then consider writing a code generator for 
custom annotations like these. You&#39;ll probably find that maintaining 
them by hand is the less onerous option. :)

@... (name = Oracle, url = &quot;file:///some/oracle/url&quot; )
@... (name = MySQL, url = &quot;file:///some/mysql/url&quot; )
@... (name = Foo, url = &quot;file:///some/foo/url&quot; )
public abstract class DbTestBase {
   ...
}

